firing squads in mali reportedly executed 29 
people this month apparently without trial amnesty international 
says the victims included an 80yearold man and a 10yearold 
boy it said 
in an appeal wednesday for an immediate halt to unlawful 
killings in the subsaharan country the worldwide human rights 
organization said the victims belonged to the tuareg ethnic group 
which had mounted an armed uprising in may and june following the 
arrest of members of their tribe 
it said more than 150 people may have been killed by the tuareg 
rebels and some 120 tuaregs were killed by government troops 
the conflict prompted malian authorities to declare a curfew and 
state of emergency in the eastern districts of gao kidal menaka 
and timbuktu and security forces were given sweeping powers to use 
force a statement by amnesty international said 
government forces subsequently took reprisals against tuareg 
civilians not involved in the conflict it said encampments 
were reportedly attacked and individuals arrested and tortured and 
otherwise illtreated 
eleven tuaregs were executed in gao on aug 3 apparently after 
being tortured and their bodies crushed by a tank and abandoned 
where they lay the statement said 
three people were executed in menaka four in kidal two in 
tinessako and nine in the tamesha area it said 
it said those shot by firing squad included akhmad ag makhakha 
80 leader of a tuareg group 10yearold bachar ag khamadin and 
issouf ag dandan an official of the ruling party the democratic 
union of the malian people 
uprisings by the nomadic tuaregs also have been reported in 
adjacent niger 
