<TEXT>
east germanys dreaded secret police force is 
dead but its chilling legacy still haunts the troubled nation 
on wednesday a top official of east germanys leading political 
party was suspended following allegations he worked for the secret 
police for 15 years 
once the heart of communist repression the secret police opened 
mail tapped phones spied on nearly everyone threw people in jail 
and kept its own arsenals 
east german officials say the secret police also harbored 
terrorists including some of west germanys most wanted fugitives 
all that came to a gradual end after the communists were toppled 
in december but the fallout forms a sinister undercurrent to this 
day 
earlier this week prosecutors in both countries said they were 
investigating allegations the secret police murdered some of those 
who ran afoul of the regime 
there has been rampant speculation about who may have been 
killed by the secret police 
the masscirculation west german newspaper bild said there is 
suspicion the secret police killed regime opponents in cold 
blood and tried to cover up the murders as accidents it says the 
victims included politicians show stars and athletes 
in the frontpage story wednesday bild raised the question of 
whether american singer dean reed was one of the victims 
reed who lived in east germany and was the darling of country 
music fans throughout the soviet bloc was found dead in a lake 
outside east berlin in june 1986 
erich honeckers communist regime said reed died in a tragic 
accident although rumors of foul play abound 
bild said reed had been considering moving back to the united 
states shortly before his death and the secret police may have 
wanted to kill him to prevent him from undermining what for the 
east german communists had been a propaganda coup 
the secret police known as the stasi once numbered about 
200000 fulltime workers and informants some say the number was 
actually higher 
virtually everyone had some kind of contact with the stasi at 
one time or another 
for many those contacts crossed the line from unavoidable 
encounters to active cooperation 
on wednesday morning a news magazine said that the general 
secretary of the christian democratic union martin kirchner was a 
paid informant for 15 years 
kirchner was even working for the intelligence network when he 
met last year with chancellor helmut kohl according to west 
germanys stern magazine 
his alleged mission was to bring back information to help stasi 
bosses prepare for the time after honeckers ouster on oct 18 
within hours after stern released its report kirchner the 
partys no 2 official was suspended pending investigation even 
though he had denied similar allegations in the past 
the east german christian democrats under prime minister lothar 
de maiziere are the nations dominant party 
kirchner isnt the first politician felled by alleged links to 
the stasi 
wolfgang schnur a leader of democratic start quit in march 
amid a furor over his reported ties to the stasi 
similar allegations also led to the resignation of ibrahim 
boehme as chief of the influential social democrats 
almost every week there have been fresh insights into stasis 
omnipresent role 
last month the democratically elected government in east berlin 
said the communists had harbored the notorious venezuelan terrorist 
carlos 
officials also believe the stasi knew well in advance of the 
april 1986 bombing of the la belle discotheque in west berlin 
the bombing left two american soldiers and a turkish woman dead 
and led to us air raids on libya 10 days later 
east germans have been arguing over what to do with former stasi 
agents since many people refuse to employ them 
but for the 82yearold former secret police boss the future 
seems fairly certain erich mielke is in jail pending investigation 
of criminal charges of abuse of power 
</TEXT>
