<TEXT>
scientists today reported progress in 
understanding how an anticancer gene protects against lung and 
breast cancer 
in a study in the british journal nature the researchers said 
that the retinoblastoma gene guards against cancer by shutting down 
a gene involved in the stimulation of cell growth 
further studies are aimed at exactly how the retinoblastoma gene 
accomplishes that said one of the authors of the study paul 
robbins of the university of pittsburgh school of medicine 
if we can understand the way in which retinoblastoma 
functions we might be able to apply that to treatment of some of 
these forms of cancer robbins said 
the research was done at the whitehead institute in cambridge 
which robbins just left his colleagues were richard mulligan and 
jonathan horowitz who has recently moved to the duke university 
medical school in durham nc 
researchers have suspected that the retinoblastoma might act by 
shutting off one or more cellgrowth genes but they didnt know 
which ones 
failure of the retinoblastoma gene is one of several steps that 
can allow the growth of not only lung and breast cancer but also 
bladder cancer prostate cancer and a rare eye cancer called 
retinoblastoma in which the gene was first identified 
the growth gene regulated by retinoblastoma is called the fos 
gene robbins showed when the retinoblastoma gene is defective and 
cannot do its job the fos gene can help trigger the runaway cell 
growth characteristic of cancer tumors 
the fos promoter its onoff switch can normally be 
stimulated in a laboratory dish by blood serum mulligans paper 
shows that when the protein made by the retinoblastoma gene is 
thrown into the dish the stimulation is slowed 
the researchers have not yet shown precisely how the protein 
acts on the fos promoter and whether for example other proteins 
are involved 
if these results lead to further experiments that show the 
retinoblastoma protein acts directly on the fos promoter its a 
breakthrough paper said edward harlow of the cold spring harbor 
laboratory an expert on tumorsuppressor genes 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

