<DOCNO> AP900816-0037 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a study today concludes that allergy testing in 
which specialists inject people with food extracts and watch for 
unpleasant symptoms is worthless 
people respond to dummy shots just as frequently as they do to 
extracts of chocolate potato wheat and other food the study 
found 
our study shows that this kind of testing is not valid said 
dr don l jewett it does not really tell you what people are 
bothered by 
jewett a surgeon at the university of california at san 
francisco directed the study which was performed by seven 
practitioners of environmental medicine 
the practice of injecting people with food extracts is a 
mainstay of environmental medicine doctors in this field attribute 
a wide variety of ailments to adverse reactions to foods chemicals 
and pollution 
dr sherry rogers of syracuse ny a member of the american 
academy of environmental medicine said she thought the study was 
flawed because doctors gave the wrong doses in their injections 
im flabbergasted she said its full of errors its a 
gross misunderstanding of the entire technique 
mainstream allergists test for allergic sensitivities with a 
scratch test typically they drop a bit of the suspected 
allergycausing substance on the broken skin and look for a rash 
by contrast those in environmental medicine inject the food 
into the skin and then wait to see if the patient feels ill 
possible symptoms include itching nose watering eyes plugged 
ears scratchy throat tiredness headache nausea dizziness 
difficulty breathing sleepiness depression chills coughing jaw 
tightening nervousness tension intestinal gas and aching legs 
if a substance triggers a response the doctor may then try to 
find a socalled neutralizing dose of the same food extract 
then the patient receives a series of these neutralizing shots 
jewett said his study questions the value of the treatment as 
well as the accuracy of the diagnostic test 
these are not charlatans he said the doctors think they 
have an answer and are trying their honest best unfortunately 
they are misguided 
his study published in the new england journal of medicine was 
performed on 18 patients during 20 sessions patients received 
either dummy shots of salt water or real food extracts neither 
they nor the doctors knew what was being given 
the patients felt symptoms following 27 percent of the active 
injections and 24 percent of the dummy shots 
jewett undertook the study after having the treatment himself 
and believing that it helped him i thought for sure it would 
show up that these shots worked he said it was a big shock to 
me to find that they didnt 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900816-0038 </DOCNO>
