housing starts in july remained mired at 
depths not seen since the last recession the government reported 
thursday and analysts forecast little if any improvement for the 
remainder of the year 
were in a severe slump said economist rob rosenblatt of 
the mortgage bankers association 
a housing recession added lawrence a hunter deputy chief 
economist with the us chamber of commerce 
the commerce department said starts of new homes and apartments 
fell for the sixth straight month down 26 percent to a seasonally 
adjusted annual rate of 115 million units 
that was the lowest level since builders began 114 million 
units at an annual rate in september 1982 two months before the 
economy emerged from the 198182 recession starts have not fallen 
for six consecutive months since junenovember 1981 
even building permits often a harbinger of future housing 
activity offered no solace they fell 26 percent to an annual 
rate of 108 million 
for the first seven months of 1990 the building pace was 96 
percent below the same period last year during all of 1989 138 
million homes were built still down from the current business 
cycle peak of 181 million in 1986 
analysts blame the situation on credit restrictions following 
the savings and loan crisis a glut of unsold homes and high 
vacancy rates in apartment buildings 
david berson chief economist with the federal national mortgage 
association said mortgage rates should decline later this year 
resulting in a slight increase in home sales and a subsequent 
pickup in singlefamily starts at year end 
john a tuccillo chief economist with the national association 
of realtors also cited economic conditions that are causing a drop 
in consumer confidence 
people simply are uncertain about what lies ahead and are 
pulling out of the market he said 
berson said the multifamily sector has very high vacancy rates 
because of overbuilding in the late 1980s 
those vacant units are going to have to be worked off before 
builders decide to start increasing the pace of multifamily 
building he said 
construction of singlefamily units fell 14 percent to an 
annual rate of 873000 units in july following a 13 percent 
decline a month earlier multifamily starts were down 65 percent 
to an annual rate of 275000 units after a 49 percent drop in june 
starts slumped in all regions except the west where 
construction jumped 87 percent to an annual rate of 317000 units 
but starts fell sharply in the south down 67 percent to an 
annual rate of 498000 units they were off 55 percent to 225000 
units in the midwest and 53 percent to 108000 units in the 
northeast 
