<TEXT>
a federal jury today began deliberating the 
cases of three former northwest airlines pilots accused of being 
drunk when they flew a passenger plane from north dakota to 
minnesota 
us district judge james rosenbaum instructed the jury to 
consider separately whether the defendants are guilty of operating 
an aircraft while under the influence of alcohol 
rosenbaum said jurors should consider this definition of being 
under the influence of alcohol when a person is so affected by 
alcohol that he lacks clearness of intellect and control of 
himself that he would otherwise have 
jurors got the case after hearing closing arguments and 
rebuttals wednesday and today 
in their closing arguments defense attorneys said their clients 
may have used poor judgment by drinking the night before flying a 
boeing 727 but they are innocent of flyingwhileintoxicated 
charges 
its not against the law to drink alcohol and fly a plane 
maybe it should be peter wold attorney for capt norman lyle 
prouse said in closing arguments wednesday its only against 
the law if you are under the influence and there is not one 
piece of evidence suggesting he was 
prouse 51 of conyers ga 1st officer robert kirchner 36 of 
highland ranch colo and flight engineer joseph balzer 35 of 
antioch tenn have been on trial since july 25 on charges of 
operating an aircraft while under the influence of alcohol 
closing arguments for balzer were scheduled today in us 
district court 
according to undisputed testimony balzer and kirchner shared 
beer from at least six pitchers and prouse consumed 15 to 20 rum 
and colas at a lounge in moorhead minn on march 7 a waitress 
testified that balzer and kirchner left about 1030 pm and prouse 
left about 1130 pm six hours later on march 8 the trio flew a 
boeing 727 with 91 passengers from fargo nd to the twin cities 
it was stupid of him kirchner to stay in the bar defense 
attorney william mauzy said 
but mauzy cautioned dont condemn them because they were in a 
bar because thats not what they are charged with 
the case marks the us justice departments first prosecution 
under a 1988 federal law prohibiting operation of a common carrier 
while under the influence of alcohol the law doesnt specify a 
bloodalcohol content for pilots to return guilty verdicts jurors 
must conclude the pilots were impaired 
defense attorneys said the smoothness of the flight showed the 
pilots were not impaired 
there wasnt anything about that flight that wasnt perfect 
mauzy said thats the best evidence you need to know about 
whether bob kirchner was impaired 
assistant us attorney elizabeth de la vega said in her closing 
argument that the pilots were able to handle flight 650 because it 
was routine she reminded jurors that a northwest pilot called as a 
defense witness described flying as hours of boredom punctuated 
by minutes of terror 
these three defendants were not capable to respond to those 
minutes of terror de la vega said 
in tests about two hours after the flight landed kirchner 
showed a bloodalcohol concentration of 006 percent balzer showed 
008 percent and prouse showed 013 percent prouses 
bloodalcohol level was more than the legal limit for driving a car 
in many states which is 010 percent 
the federal felony carries a maximum 15 years in prison and a 
250000 fine 
the three pilots were fired for violating northwests 12hour 
prohibition against drinking before flying 
in a report in the new england journal of medicine today two 
doctors said even a little alcohol can hinder pilots ability to 
fly and recommended that federal rules bar pilots from taking the 
controls until at least 12 hours after their last drink 
the weight of the evidence suggests that even small amounts of 
alcohol can have a profoundly negative effect on flight safety 
said drs jack g modell and james m mountz of the university of 
michigan 
