<TEXT>
the federal election commission on thursday 
asked for input on a proposal to ban political action committees of 
companies at least half owned by foreigners 
the 50 commission vote came several weeks after the senate 
voted 7327 to include a similar proposal in a campaign finance 
reform bill 
the fec plan by commissioner john warren mcgarry establishes a 
60day public comment period ending oct 12 the commission set an 
oct 31 public hearing 
under the proposed rule any corporation with 50 percent or more 
foreign ownership would be defined as a foreign national unable to 
participate in federal elections subsidiaries in the united states 
failing to qualify would not be allowed to contribute to campaigns 
or spend money on any federal election 
the commission also sought comments on how it should enforce the 
rule and on any other issues involving participation by foreign 
nationals in federal elections 
currently the fec allows us subsidiaries of foreign firms to 
have pacs provided the foreign owners do not control or direct 
operation of the committees 
supporting the proposal were commission chairwoman lee ann 
elliott and commissioners thomas j josefiak scott thomas and 
danny lee mcdonald 
the senate language sponsored by sen lloyd bentsen dtexas 
was approved as part of a bill that would impose spending ceilings 
on candidates and also try to eliminate pacs altogether 
bentsen said his amendment was intended to give legislative 
underpinning to the fec in case the senate drops the proposed ban 
on pacs in conference or if the prohibition is ruled 
unconstitutional 
bentsen cited congressional research service statistics showing 
that pacs of foreignowned companies contributed 28 million to 
candidates in the 1988 elections a 19 percent increase over 1986 
the current system he said allows foreignowned companies to 
pressure employees of their us subsidiaries to use the pac 
muscle in ways acceptable to the corporate masters in london 
frankfurt or tokyo 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

