<TEXT>
albania announced thursday that it would 
adhere to the nuclear weapons nonproliferation treaty in effect 
committing itself not to manufacture such arms 
the presidium of the peoples assembly decided by decree 
the adherence of our country to the treaty said a report by the 
albanian state ata news agency monitored in vienna 
albania has no nuclear weapons nor does it possess nuclear 
reactors which give off radioactive waste that could be used in 
the manufacture of such arms 
the declaration thus appeared to have a mostly symbolic 
character although experts at the international atomic energy 
agency said albania possibly had several research reactors at 
universities producing sufficient waste to produce some weapons 
the decision announced by albanias state ata news agency was 
the latest sign that the small balkan country was determined to 
move away from its isolationist reputation and be party to 
international treaties and conventions albania would be the 141st 
country to accept the nonproliferation treaty 
diplomatic ties with moscow were reestablished last month after 
a nearly three decade hiatus occasioned by ideological differences 
albania also has served notice it wants to renew ties with 
washington 
moves to increase relations with foreign countries have been 
accompanied by internal reforms that have loosened the communist 
partys omnipresent grip but the communist leadership has served 
notice it will not permit democracy of the kind that has 
transformed the rest of east europe 
the government announced july 31 that it would allow the 
formation of joint ventures and other forms of foreign 
participation in the economy and decreed limited freedoms to stage 
public demonstrations 
those moves appeared designed to ease economic backwardness and 
provide a safety valve for a restive population dissatisfied with a 
low living standard and lack of personal freedoms 
in recent weeks albanian citizens demanding change forced their 
way into foreign embassies in tirana and were allowed to leave the 
country 
</TEXT>
