homicides are the leading cause of fatal 
onthejob injuries among american women according to a federal 
study released thursday 
if a womans going to die from an injury at work shes 
probably going to be murdered said catherine bell an 
epidemiologist with the national institute for occupational safety 
and health a division of the national centers for disease control 
fortytwo percent of workplace trauma deaths of women in the 
united states from 1980 to 1985 were homicides the cdc reported 
jobrelated motor vehicle accidents were second at around 39 
percent 
by comparison homicides accounted for 12 percent of mens 
occupational fatalities for both sexes nationwide about 13 
percent of onthejob trauma deaths during 198085 were homicides 
the cdc reported 
health institute investigators identified 950 female 
occupational homicides over the sixyear period of that number 
389 or 41 percent worked in the retail field 
although research is not complete it seems that strangers in 
the store not coworkers are responsible for most workplace 
killings of women ms bell said 
they appear to be robberyassociated crimes in the retail 
trade she said 
the killings peaked from december to march sixtyfour percent 
of the killings were committed with guns 19 percent were 
stabbings the workplace homicide rate for black women was nearly 
double that for white women 
the cdc did not release figures for causes of workplace trauma 
deaths among women other than homicides and vehicular accidents 
the reports findings suggest public health professionals need 
to devise ways to reduce womens risk in the workplace ms bell 
said 
