robert mapplethorpes sexually explicit 
photographs have drawn the scrutiny of the federal communications 
commission which is investigating complaints against a public 
television station that aired some of the pictures 
boston station wgbhtv included the photos in a 10 pm newscast 
july 31 during a segment about mapplethorpes work which went on 
exhibit at the institute of contemporary art the next day 
the exhibit has generated heated debate since last year when 
sen jesse helms rnc attacked it prompting congress to limit 
federal grants to art deemed obscene 
the director of a cincinnati art gallery that exhibited the 
photographs is being tried for pandering obscenity a few of the 
photographs depict naked children or homoerotic sex 
at least three people have complained to the fcc since wgbh 
showed some of the photographs among them was donald wildmon head 
of the american family association in tupelo miss who sent a 
videotape of the broadcast to the fcc 
a letter from wildmon described the broadcast as nothing more 
than the sensational presentation of potentially obscene material 
eric brass attorney for wgbh defended the stations decision 
it just is not obscene brass said thursday i believe we 
have the right to do what we did in the context of a serious news 
program we cannot be in the position of censoring debate about 
censorship thats what it would come down to 
the fcc has not decided what action if any should be taken 
said roger holberg an fcc attorney 
if material is judged to be obscene it can be banned entirely 
from being broadcast holberg said but material deemed to be 
indecent is given more leeway 
under its current rules the fcc prohibits indecent material 
from appearing on the airwaves prior to 8 pm attempting to put 
it beyond the reach of unsupervised children holberg said 
but last year the fcc citing evidence that children often watch 
late television adopted a rule that would let the agency restrict 
the broadcast of indecent material 24 hours a day that rule was 
challenged by broadcasters and other groups and the us court of 
appeals in washington is weighing whether it can be enforced 
the fcc defines indecency as materials that portray sexual or 
excretory activities or organs in terms patently offensive as 
measured by contemporary community standards holberg said 
officials at the television station said the photographs were 
included in the broadcast because they were at the center of the 
news 
we wanted to let the public know what the controversy was 
about and let them decide for themselves said station 
spokeswoman julie eggleston 
