sudden gasoline pump price jumps at the start 
of the persian gulf crisis have prompted four senators to propose 
antiprofiteering legislation 
the legislation would make those who profiteer on commodities 
such as oil and gas during times of national emergency subject to 
prison terms and hefty fines 
the original sponsors of the legislation expected to be 
introduced when congress reconvenes next month are senators joseph 
i liebermann dconn richard bryan dnev pail simon dill 
and larry pressler rsd 
the proposed legislation to be called the national emergency 
antiprofiteering act would 
allow the president to declare a national economic emergency 
when international or domestic crises threaten to seriously disrupt 
the us economy 
prohibit excessive price increases in oil gasoline diesel 
aviation fuel heating oil and propane when such a national 
economic emergency involving oil products exists 
give the justice department power to investigate allegations of 
profiteering 
give the federal government power to seek forfeiture of any 
illegally obtained profits from the oil companies for the benefit 
of consumers 
profiteers would be subject to up to five years in prison 
500000 in fines and double damages if convicted of profiteering 
according to the bills sponsors 
