transportation secretary samuel skinner said 
thursday that civilian airlines stand ready to give up commercial 
flights to ferry soldiers to the middle east but he is optimistic 
that it wont be necessary 
skinner also said that the governments reserve of merchant 
ships with civilian crews is being prepared to supply growing us 
military operations following iraqs invasion of kuwait 
if it means they have to cancel flights and divert aircraft 
they will do so skinner said after meeting individually with 
several airline presidents wednesday and thursday he had called 
the carrier executives in to discuss the impact of increasing jet 
fuel prices on the industry and its passengers 
skinner speaking to reporters in his office praised airlines 
for supplying hired charters that have already carried some troops 
he declined to say how many airlines had been involved 
several airlines contacted on wednesday said there had been no 
disruption of normal flights but that the military had notified 
them to be prepared to activate the civil reserve air fleet if 
necessary the fleet is made up of several passenger jets 
designated for use by the military in times of crisis 
on the fuel issue skinner said industry leaders told him they 
anticipate a financial crunch because of rising fuel prices and 
fares will have to go up 
he said there is no evidence of price gouging in efforts by the 
airlines to increase prices but market demand has forced many of 
them to scale back initial plans for increases 
several airlines had announced 10 percent hikes to take effect 
this week but most have scaled back to 53 percent and some are 
offering even lower fares than those in effect before the gulf 
crisis skinner said this reflects public resistance to the 
increases rather than any pressure from the government to roll back 
ticket prices 
the transportation secretary said several ships were being 
prepared from the seagoing ready reserve fleet which is a supply 
of 96 merchant vessels mothballed by the military at several ports 
for emergency use 
the ships are surplus civilian vessels purchased by the 
military each is supposed to be maintained so it can be ready for 
use in 510 days 
skinner acknowledged some difficulty in recruiting crews for the 
vessels but said this was being worked out with maritime union 
officials 
this is the biggest test of the ready reserve fleet we have 
ever had and it seems to be working fairly well skinner said 
skinner said he was forming a task force of airline industry 
union and government officials to look into ways the aviation 
industry can save on fuel costs 
he said airline stockholders are likely to end up absorbing 
about half of the increased cost and that some financially troubled 
carriers face a serious challenge 
this could take them from a modest profit year to a very 
modest or loss year industrywide skinner said 
the secretary said he met with officials of united trans world 
northwest pan american and delta airlines and talked by phone with 
officials of some other carriers 
