<TEXT>
heart disease in this country could be reduced 
considerably if americans would just get some exercise the 
national centers for disease control said thursday 
for instance the cdc said more than 22000 deaths a year in 
new york state alone are attributable to a sedentary lifestyle and 
coronary heart disease 
earlier this summer the cdc released a 37state survey showing 
that 57 percent of those questioned didnt get as much as three 
20minute sessions of physical activity a week 
the agency then calculated for 11 different states the number 
of coronary heart disease deaths that could have been prevented 
with exercise the formula took into account deaths from heart 
disease in 1987 the percentage of people getting little or no 
exercise and the probability that sedentary people are 19 times 
as likely to die from coronary heart disease 
in addition to the 22000 in new york the cdc projected 12000 
preventable heart disease deaths in florida 10000 in ohio and 
5000 in missouri even tiny rhode island had more than 1100 heart 
disease deaths that could have been prevented with proper exercise 
the atlantabased cdc calculated 
not all states were included just those which have launched 
physical fitnessheart disease programs and such data projections 
must be interpreted with caution the cdc said 
but the estimated number of preventable coronary heart disease 
deaths calculated from these data are substantial the report 
said 
other states included in the cdc report were tennessee with 
about 4600 preventable deaths alabama 2900 south carolina 
2700 washington 2600 west virginia 2100 and maine 1200 
new yorks high ranking in the projections 40 percent of its 
heart disease deaths being deemed preventable was a result of its 
poor showing in the cdcs 37state exercise survey 
seventyfour percent of the new yorkers in that study said they 
didnt get three 20minute episodes of physical activity a week 
the worst in the nation 
the state of washington on the other hand was best in the 
country 45 percent of its people reported getting enough exercise 
to avoid the sedentary classification 
another leading cause of coronary heart disease is excessive 
serum cholesterol federal health officials say about 30 percent of 
americans between ages 20 and 74 have elevated serum cholesterol 
levels 
