<TEXT>
a man charged with raping a woman with a 
multiple personality disorder pleaded innocent thursday after the 
victim alternated between three identities during courtroom 
questioning 
the case raises new questions about sexual consent and mental 
illness the victim says two of her personalities were raped but 
defendant mark a peterson contends one of the womans 
personalities consented 
during questioning the 26yearold oshkosh woman closed her 
eyes gently and paused as she moved between her personalities 
herself and characters called franny and jennifer at the request 
of district attorney joseph paulus 
can i have jennifer the one who likes to have fun paulus 
asked 
of course the woman replied smiling momentarily before 
closing her eyes a few seconds later she opened her eyes and 
blurted hi mr paulus in a slightly higher voice 
winnebago county circuit judge robert hawley required the woman 
to take an oath each time she changed personalities and the 
lawyers formally introduced themselves to the different 
personalities assuming such knowledge did not transfer between 
personalities 
during her hourlong testimony the woman described how she 
believed peterson raped her in his car after she told him she 
suffered from a mental illness 
the woman said she had been raped june 11 while she was 
jennifer a funloving promiscuous 20yearold woman who liked to 
dance to rock music 
after the couple had sex he said can i have franny back i 
said ok the woman told the court 
peterson 29 of oshkosh sat quietly and showed no emotion as 
the woman testified he later appeared briefly before the judge and 
pleaded innocent to a charge of seconddegree sexual assault 
the charge carries a maximum of 10 years in prison on 
conviction hawley agreed there was probable cause to bind peterson 
over for trial but did not immediately set a trial date peterson 
is free on a signature bond 
legal experts agree the case is problematic on several fronts 
if the woman is not palpably mentally ill then the 
prosecution has problems said leonard kaplan a university of 
wisconsin law school professor observing the case in oshkosh a 
city of 50000 in eastcentral wisconsin if she is mentally ill 
she cant consent 
the victim has as many as 21 different personalities a mental 
illness that typically develops after a traumatic childhood 
experience psychologists said 
she told police two of her personalities jennifer and emily a 
vulnerable 6yearold girl were assaulted by peterson in june 
the defense counters the woman consented and peterson had no 
idea the woman was mentally ill 
paulus said he will be forced to introduce several of the 
victims personalities to a jury through her testimony during the 
trial expected in october 
i wouldnt say im looking forward to it it is unusual 
paulus said you are talking about a subject matter that is 
somewhat foreign to everybody 
defense lawyer edward salzsieder has asked that the charge be 
dismissed 
there is a question of when does anybody know a person is 
mentally ill he said 
according to court records the woman met peterson june 9 at a 
park when the victim was portraying a personality she called franny 
two days later peterson went to the womans home and invited 
her out for coffee at the restaurant the woman reportedly 
introduced some of her personalities to peterson including 
jennifer the records said 
after the pair left the restaurant jennifer agreed to have 
sexual intercourse at the mans suggestion in a car peterson told 
police 
the criminal complaint alleged peterson noted that during sex 
the womans 6yearold personality emily appeared before the 
woman eventually became franny again 
neighbors have told police they warned peterson that the woman 
had a mental disorder 
paulus said he must prove three things that the victim had a 
mental illness that she was incapable of appraising her own 
conduct and that peterson knew about the illness 
they all present roadblocks he said adding that he has 
become well enough acquainted with the victim that he can summon 
her various personalities at will 
it could turn out to be the battle of the experts and 
persuading a jury which expert is right kaplan said 
multiplepersonality disorder is usually caused by early 
childhood trauma especially sexual abuse and affects one person 
in 10000 said dr nancy perry a milwaukee clinical psychologist 
the patient separates one part of his or herself from another to 
avoid facing the trauma perry said 
</TEXT>
