libya on thursday called for replacing the 
us military in the persian gulf with arab league and un forces 
in lima peru un secretarygeneral javier perez de cuellar 
said the use of military power to enforce un sanctions against 
iraq without approval from the un security council would violate 
the uns charter 
american officials have said the usled multinational force 
blocking ships with iraqi cargo is acting in line with the un 
sanctions 
responding to another development in the regional crisis the 
five permanent members of the un security council met privately 
to discuss iraqs order that americans and britons in kuwait 
assemble in hotels 
libyan leader moammar gadhafi in a letter to the un 
secretarygeneral called for an emergency security council meeting 
in geneva to remove us forces there was no decision on a 
meeting but consultations were under way 
gadhafi said us troops in saudi arabia should be replaced by 
arab league forces and us naval personnel in the persian gulf 
should be replaced by un forces 
in his comments during a press conference at perus foreign 
ministry perez de cuellar said that article 41 of the un charter 
states that any blockade has to have un security council approval 
as long as that is not the case he said any 
intervention whatever the country would not be in accordance with 
the letter or spirit of the united nations charter 
the five permanent security council members the united states 
britain china france and the soviet union were meeting to 
discuss the iraqi order that americans and britons in iraq gather 
at hotels because of unspecified threats in washington the us 
state department said it was protesting the order 
diplomats said security council members were also expected to 
discuss the situation of those already detained the revival of the 
security councils military staff committee and a possible un 
military role and compliance with un economic sanctions against 
iraq 
the soviet union has been pressing for a broader un role in 
controlling regional conflicts and has said it would only 
participate in a military operation in the gulf under the un flag 
a special committee of the security council is studying an 
interim report from perez de cuellar about compliance with the un 
economic embargo against iraq though the embargo is intended to be 
binding un members voted no specific measures to enforce it 
the committee is to meet friday canadian diplomats said they 
intended to raise the issue of violations of the embargo and how 
the committee would monitor compliance beyond official government 
statements 
if the committee decides the boycott is not being honored the 
security council can declare a military blockade and appeal to 
member states to enforce it 
thirtytwo of the 159 un members had filed compliance reports 
by wednesday and all were honoring the sanctions a full un 
report is due by the end of the month 
bulgaria was the only reporting nation to emphasize the 
hardships imposed by the compliance and it reserved the right to 
appeal to the council for relief it said however that it was 
fully implementing the embargo 
under the un charter nations that suffer because of their 
compliance with un enforcement actions may appeal to the council 
for relief usually in the form of an exemption 
the nations that filed reports wednesday were argentina 
australia austria brazil bulgaria canada chile cyprus 
czechoslovakia finland france east germany west germany 
hungary italy ivory coast japan malaysia netherlands new 
zealand norway panama south korea romania singapore solomon 
islands spain sweden turkey united kingdom united states 
uruguay 
