scientists may have found a potential 
natural ally in their effort to wipe out the imported melaleuca 
tree before it takes over the everglades a cankerproducing 
fungus found in dying trees 
widespread use of the organism must wait until scientists are 
sure it can be used safely and effectively said roger webb a tree 
pathologist at the university of florida department of forest 
resources 
scientists believe as many as 6 billion melaleuca are in south 
florida covering onefourth of the everglades and they could 
cover threefourths of the everglades by the end of the decade 
webbs work and that of his assistants along with tests by a 
laboratory in england have tentatively identified the fungus as 
botryosphaeria ribis he said 
the fungus widespread in tropical and temperate regions causes 
rot in fruit and cankers in the bark of trees ranging from avocado 
to elm spores are produced in lowlying areas during wet periods 
and are spread by rain and wind once inside bark the fungus 
spreads through wood cutting off the flow of nutrients and water 
leaves wilt and die as do branches above the canker 
since 1983 biologists have been killing the melaleuca by 
cutting into the bark and squirting herbicides into the wound they 
believe the gashes provided points of entry for the fungus and the 
stress from the herbicide made the tree more vulnerable 
melaleuca trees were imported from australia decades ago as a 
possible source of lumber but quickly got out of hand the smelly 
tree causes headaches and other allergic reactions and sucks four 
times as much water from the ground as the sawgrass it replaces 
a task force of federal state and local scientists recently 
began a 25year eradication program they say may cost up to 10 
million 
</TEXT>
