but the trust faces 130000 more claims it cant meet it has 
paid only two thirds of the money for cases settled and is 
hemorrhaging cash to defend lawsuits in unresolved cases 21 
million from january through june a federal judge has frozen its 
spending and ordered its overhaul 
as judges nationwide craft a solution to the nations biggest 
product liability issue the manville trust is blamed for 
aggravating the asbestos mess 
it couldnt have been worse gita rothschild an attorney 
for several companies that made asbestos said wednesday the 
idea could have worked it was mismanaged 
trust officials deny they created its fiscal black hole they 
say it resulted from an unanticipated number of claims 
unexpectedly high settlements and quick resolution of early cases 
the trust didnt write the original script but we have been 
charged with carrying out what was ordained donald m blinken 
one of five trustees responsible for the washingtonbased 
operation said in an interview 
the trust has had no problem paying its claimants he said 
the trust simply has never been given enough money 
formation of the trust was supported by a wide majority of 
manville corp creditors plaintiffs lawyers representatives of 
future claimants codefendants and the company itself 
the trust is legally separate from manville which sought 
chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in 1982 because of lawsuits over 
asbestos an insulation material that causes lung cancer and other 
repiratory ailments 
insurance payments and manville cash and securities made the 
trust worth about 3 billion but it now has only 153 million in 
cash well short of whats needed to pay previously settled claims 
a 375 million cash infusion from manville isnt due until august 
1991 
the trust owns about 80 percent of manvilles stock on which it 
relies as a guaranteed source of future income even it sold the 
stock today there wouldnt be enough money to pay pending claims 
lawyers assert 
though manville is protected from further lawsuits publicity 
about the trusts problems has helped push down manville stock to 
around 6 a share from over 10 last october 
criticism of the trust centers on the size and timing of 
payments to victims and on fees received by plaintiffs lawyers the 
bulk of trust money went to settle early cases not necessarily 
from victims whose illnesses required immediate attention 
the plan didnt say they had to pay an inordinate amount on 
the first 15000 cases said richard f scruggs a plaintiffs 
lawyer in pascagoula miss handling thousands of cases 
the trust tries to take credit for paying out quickly when 
they were paying it out without any regard to the number of future 
cases or their severity he said 
trust officials blame the reorganization plan which authorized 
settlement on a firstcome firstserved basis the bankruptcy 
judge in charge burton r lifland refused to limit fees to 
plaintiffs lawyers typically one third of settlements 
marianna smith the trusts executive director said the fees 
had nothing to do with settlement size an average of 43231 per 
claim to date compared with an estimated 25000 when the trust was 
formed 
but defense lawyers allege their colleagues on the plaintiffs 
side inflated settlement requests to make more money they say no 
one forced the trust to pay as much as it did especially when many 
early manville claimants had received money from other asbestos 
defendants 
is it in the plaintiffs best interest to tell their clients to 
take 25000 when they could bang manville over the head and take 
50000 rothschild said 
they dissipated the money in an unbelievably short period of 
time paying people who had already been paid with no regard to the 
post1982 and future claimants she said when we started 
seeing the payments out in the field it was no surprise they ran 
out of money when they did 
us judge jack b weinstein who ordered the trusts 
restructuring and a spending freeze due to expire sept 6 said 
this week he expects the trust to be combined with funds from 
asbestos companies who say they lack money to pay claims the money 
would be paid to victims in a classaction lawsuit 
in the meantime weinstein wants the trust to begin paying 
claims based on medical need an infusion of cash is expected 
possibly as a special dividend on manville stock or through the 
sale of some assets 
trust officials said they have proposed resolving asbestos 
claims for other companies in addition to manville to help clear an 
asbestos court backlog of 90000 lawsuits nationwide 
