<TEXT>
even a little alcohol can hinder pilots ability 
to fly and federal rules should bar them from taking the controls 
until at least 12 hours after their last drink two doctors 
recommended today 
in a report in the new england journal of the medicine the 
doctors both pilots recommended sharply tightening federal 
aviation administration regulations 
the weight of the evidence suggests that even small amounts of 
alcohol can have a profoundly negative effect on flight safety 
the doctors wrote 
under their proposed changes 
pilots would not be allowed to fly if their blood alcohol 
levels were more than 01 percent current federal rules allow 04 
percent in most states the illegal level of alcohol in the blood 
for drunken driving is 010 percent but five states california 
colorado oregon maine and utah have set the level at a a more 
stringent 008 percent 
they would need to wait at least 12 hours after drinking before 
flying the current bottletothrottle rule is eight hours 
flying would be prohibited within 24 hours of consuming five or 
more drinks or when hung over 
pilots would be quizzed about their knowledge of alcohols 
effects when taking licensing exams 
the rules were proposed by drs jack g modell and james m 
mountz of the university of michigan 
they also recommended studying the possibility of equipping 
planes with locks that require pilots to pass coordination tests 
before they can start their planes these devices require pilots to 
perform a brief task to check their reaction times and shortterm 
memories among other things 
the doctors noted that surveys have shown that between 10 
percent and 30 percent of pilots involved in fatal accidents caused 
by pilot error have alcohol in their blood 
they said that pilots may still perform poorly many hours after 
heavy drinking even though alcohol has virtually disappeared from 
their blood 
closing arguments were scheduled to resume today in the case of 
