<TEXT>
falling energy prices helped hold down the 
overall increase in consumer prices in july the government said 
today in what analysts believe will be the last moderate inflation 
report before the persian gulf crisis produces higher oil costs 
the labor department said its consumer price index rose 04 
percent last month despite a 07 percent drop in energy costs 
the overall july gain followed a slightly brisker 05 percent 
advance in june and a modest 02 percent rise in may it was a bit 
larger than the 03 percent expected by most economists and was 
regarded as a worrisome sign going into august 
it tells us that inflation was wellentrenched going into the 
oil shock while not horrendous it was very much a part of the 
scene said economist robert dederick of northern trust co in 
chicago 
the aug 2 iraqi invasion of kuwait has sent oil prices 
spiraling since the government surveyed prices for todays report 
even without the oil shock inflation for the first seven months 
of the year was running at a 58 percent annual rate compared with 
46 percent for all of 1989 
also today the commerce department said housing starts 
continued to plummet in july falling 26 percent to their lowest 
level since september 1982 when the economy was about to emerge 
from the 198182 recession it was the sixth straight monthly 
decline 
despite weakness in housing persistent inflation leaves the 
federal reserve board little leeway to stimulate the economy with 
lower interest rates dederick said 
stock and bond prices fell after the economic reports were 
released the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks declined 
1931 points to 272896 in the first half hour of trading 
the labor department said the cost of shelter shot up 09 
percent the same as in june that accounted for half the overall 
increase in prices much of the cpi rise in shelter prices was 
attributed to a 51 percent increase in the cost of outoftown 
lodging 
food and beverage prices were up 04 percent the third 
consecutive increase but a far smaller one than junes 07 percent 
gain 
the price of fruit and vegetables rose 16 percent reflecting a 
322 percent jump in the price of bananas and a 171 percent gain 
in the cost of lettuce 
pork prices were down a slight 02 percent the first decline 
since september a period in which they rose 191 percent 
egg prices dropped 82 percent in july nonalcoholic beverages 
were up 09 percent while fats and oils rose 11 percent 
transportation costs rose 03 percent last month gasoline 
prices which had risen 25 percent in june fell 03 percent 
new car prices reacting to lackluster sales fell 03 percent 
the sixth consecutive decline but used car prices rose 07 
percent the largest gain since january 1989 
clothing prices fell 02 percent the third consecutive drop 
price increases for some fall and winter clothing only partially 
offset further discounts on spring and summer clothes 
medical care prices continued a long string of stubbornly high 
advances they rose 09 percent in july and were 92 percent higher 
than a year ago 
the cost of smoking aside from its health effects rose steeply 
in july up 27 percent after a 24 percent jump in june tobacco 
prices were 109 percent higher than a year ago 
prices excluding the volatile food and energy categories rose a 
brisk 06 percent economists often take that measure as a better 
gauge of underlying inflationary pressures 
that socalled core rate has stayed high largely because the 
weakening economy hasnt yet pushed unemployment up appreciably 
thus wages and the cost of services which make up 55 percent of 
the consumer index have been rising steadily 
the various changes put the index for all consumer prices at 
1304 in july that means that a hypothetical selection of goods 
that cost 10 in the 198284 base period cost 1304 last month up 
from 1244 a year earlier 
economist donald ratajczak of georgia state university predicted 
august prices would be up 07 percent overall because of the 
energy rise 
rarely have changing energy prices moved so rapidly through 
the pipeline to the consumer he said within hours of the 
iraqi invasion of kuwait prices were rising at the corner gasoline 
station as suppliers feared that consumers would exhaust available 
supplies 
economist bruce steinberg of merrill lynch expects prices will 
feel the direct effect of the energy shock through november after 
that the question is whether the oil spiral will trigger an 
increase in prices of seemingly unrelated goods and services 
lingering upward pressure on the core inflation rate could 
persist in subsequent months but the net effect would be muted 
because economic weakness is likely to lead to compensating 
downward pressure on labor costs he said 
</TEXT>
