<TEXT>
more crude oil production might numerically 
offset most of the oil lost in the embargo of iraq and kuwait but 
environmental and political concerns could limit the us supply of 
gasoline industry sources said today 
world producers probably could increase their crude output by up 
to 35 million barrels per day by the fourth quarter said an 
executive with a major us oil company who spoke to reporters on 
condition that he and his company not be identified 
though that comes close to the 4 million barrels lost daily 
through the international boycott of iraqi and kuwaiti oil the 
extra crude would not necessarily accommodate us needs the 
executive said 
there are certain crudes and certain products and certain 
suppliers you cant turn to he said much of the oil would have 
to come from iran and libya which domestic companies would not buy 
in addition many refineries that could increase output are not 
capable of producing unleaded gasoline or other products that meet 
us environmental standards which are stricter than those imposed 
by other nations 
the stuff thats idle today does not serve the purposes of the 
us said another major oil company executive also speaking on 
condition of anonymity 
three modern refineries have been knocked out of the world 
market because they are located in kuwait which was invaded by 
iraq on aug 2 the kuwaiti refineries had a rough capacity of 
600000 barrels of refined oil per day some of which was arriving 
in the southern united states through the gulf of mexico the 
industry sources said 
the executives also predicted that opec nations will not 
immediately increase production until they allow time for oil 
inventories to drop 
one of the executives called the current oil crisis a long 
term problem he predicted the price of crude will stay high as 
will the price of gasoline in coming months 
in late morning trading today on the new york mercantile 
exchange the price of west texas intermediate the benchmark us 
crude had risen 42 cents per barrel to 2688 as traders remained 
uncertain about the prospects of increased production by members of 
the organization of petroleum exporting countries 
</TEXT>
