<TEXT>
general electric cos aircraft engines 
division announced thursday it will eliminate 1500 jobs in its 
us operations by 1992 because of cuts in military defense 
spending 
ge aircraft engines based in this cincinnati suburb said 500 
people would be laid off by the end of 1990 at its evendale and 
lynn mass jet engine plants 
it expects the rest of the reduction to be accomplished by 
attrition through the end of 1992 at the two plants which produce 
engines for military and commercial aircraft 
the reduction will affect mostly salaried employees but also 
will include some hourly production workers ge aircraft engines 
spokeswoman paula kollstedt said 
about 47 percent of ge aircraft engines 68 billion in revenue 
last year came from military contracts that percentage is expected 
to decrease to 35 percent by 1992 the company said 
ge said its commercial jet engine business has a 20 billion 
backlog for delivery during the next several years 
unfortunately the increase in ges commercial engine business 
will not be enough to offset predicted cuts in military spending 
said brian rowe senior vice president of ge aircraft engines we 
regret that our existing workload is not large enough to support 
current employment levels 
rowe said the reduction is necessary to keep his division 
competitive as the united states reduces defense spending 
ms kollstedt said the number of layoffs and attrition losses 
could change depending on the companys continuing review of the 
situation 
this is our best estimate at this time she said 
the evendale plant is one of the largest employers in the 
cincinnati area with a workforce of about 18000 people ge 
aircraft engines employs 37250 worldwide 
united auto workers union local 647 which represents almost 
5000 production employees at the evendale plant said ge informed 
the union thursday morning of the job cutbacks charlie highlander 
vice president of local 647 declined comment 
</TEXT>
