<TEXT>
saudi arabia today called for an 
emergency meeting of the organization of petroleum exporting 
countries to discuss how to deal with the oil market in light of 
the iraqkuwait crisis 
saudi oil minister hisham nazer said the kingdom along with 
other unidentified members of the cartel have asked for an 
immediate opec meeting to discuss a unified decision on dealing 
with conditions of the market 
no date or site for the meeting was announced 
the minister in a short official statement denied the kingdom 
had notified any of its customers of any cutbacks in oil supply for 
september 
earlier in the day the japanese foreign ministry said saudi 
arabia had notified us european and japanese oil companies of a 
15 percent to 20 percent cutback in its oil supply for the month of 
september 
the japanese officials said no reason was given for the reported 
planned cutbacks which followed reports that the saudis would 
boost daily output from 54 million barrels to more than 7 million 
barrels to offset the loss of iraqi oil being blocked by a 
worldwide embargo when iraq invaded kuwait on aug 2 it increased 
its share of the worlds oil reserves to 20 percent 
at the most recent opec meeting which concluded in geneva 
switzerland on july 27 the 13 opec ministers raised the target 
price of oil by 3 a barrel to 21 a barrel they also agreed not 
to exceed the production ceiling of 225 million barrels a day 
until the end of the year 
earlier this year the price declined to the low 16 range 
partly because crude output by opec and other producers was 
outpacing world demand 
prices began rising earlier this summer after the cartel reached 
an agreement to restrain production prices shot sharply higher 
after the invasion of kuwait on speculation that iraq might attack 
saudi arabia the worlds largest oil exporter 
at the opec meeting in july iraq accused kuwait and the united 
arab emirates of overproducing oil and thus driving down prices 
iraq which relies heavily on oil sales to keep its economy afloat 
used the dispute over oil and territory to justify its invasion of 
kuwait on aug 2 
takahiro nakamae of japans ministry of international trade and 
industrys petroleum planning department said earlier today that 
even if the report of the planned saudi oil cutback for september 
is confirmed it will have little effect on japans overall oil 
supply 
japan he noted has 142 days worth of oil in reserve 
japan has agreed to participate in a full trade embargo on iraq 
and kuwait which were supplying 420000 barrels a day or 11 
percent of japans oil imports japan is dependent on the middle 
east for nearly 70 percent of its oil virtually all of which is 
imported 
but nakamae said japan can offset the iraqi and kuwait oil and 
the reported planned cutback by the saudis by importing more oil 
from other sources 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

