<TEXT>
empire federal savings of america has sold 
its 900 million auto loan portfolio to a general electric 
subsidiary as part of the federal governments restructuring of the 
seized thrift 
the purchase is ge capital auto financial services first major 
push into the business of holding and servicing auto loans said 
keith helming manager of business analysis for the ge capital 
unit ge capital already is involved in other autorelated 
businesses such as automobile leasing 
empire of america was seized by savings and loan regulators in 
january as part of the nationwide sampl bailout regulators have said 
they plan to sell the buffalobased thrifts major assets 
separately and hope to complete the process by the end of 
september 
ge plans to buy between 200 million and 400 million worth of 
auto loans each year to maintain the size of the empire portfolio 
and eventually make it grow helming said 
he said the company believes this is a good time to enter the 
auto loan market because many banks are selling assets and 
servicing rights he said some banks have found that the auto loan 
business has not met their profit expectations while others have 
been forced to sell auto loan assets in order to raise money to 
meet higher federal capital guidelines 
the purchase includes empires auto loan servicing facility in 
amherst which employs 100 people helming said those employees 
would be retained and the facility eventually will be expanded as 
the auto loan business grows 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

