<TEXT>
the federal reserves rejection of the merger 
of bank of new york and a connecticut bank holding company may be a 
signal that banks should build strong capital reserves analysts 
said thursday 
the central bank rarely rejects a bank merger however late 
wednesday it announced it had denied the application from bank of 
new york to acquire northeast bancorp inc which owns the union 
trust co of stamford conn 
i dont think theres any question that regulators are sending 
a very loud and clear message to the banking community capital 
is king said james j mcdermott jr an analyst with keefe 
bruyette and woods 
capital represents stockholders investment in a bank and acts 
as a cushion between losses and the governments deposit insurance 
fund 
the feds action comes a month after senate testimony from 
federal reserve chairman alan greenspan who said strong capital 
requirements are the best means of ensuring stability in the 
banking system 
bank of new york and northeast first discussed a merger seven 
years ago bank of new york with 464 billion in assets at the 
end of last year was the nations eighth largest bank according 
to sheshunoff information services of austin texas union trust 
with 35 billion in assets was the third largest in connecticut 
but the merger agreement reached in 1986 turned into a bitter 
dispute over what constituted a fair price for new haven 
connbased northeast northeast had placed its takeover value at 
about 500 million bank of new york which had concerns about the 
value of northeasts loans valued the company at 1956 million 
the disagreement led some analysts to speculate that the new 
york bank wanted to back out of the deal it also led northeast to 
file a breachofcontract lawsuit in may seeking 350 million in 
damages 
in its order denying the merger the fed noted capital 
adequacy is an especially important factor in the analysis of 
banking holding company expansion proposals it said capital of 
the combined banks would not be substantially above the boards 
minimum capital levels 
another factor in the rejection mcdermott said likely was 
weakening commercial real estate values in the northeast which are 
cutting into bank profits 
combinations in the northeast at this point in time are not 
being looked at favorably given the current economic outlook he 
said 
