<TEXT>
the federal reserve bank of new york temporarily 
moved its fedwire electronic funds transfer system out of new 
york on thursday because of a power problem averting what could 
have been an unexpected bank holiday in the nations financial 
center 
the fedwire is the central banks funds and securities transfer 
service the principal means of transferring money between banks 
the new york feds fedwire branch is the nations busiest 
shuttling 900 billion worth of securities and funds among banks 
daily 
peter bakstansky a vice president of the new york fed said the 
power problem was an indirect result of a local blackout on monday 
which cut electricity to the fed office and many other buildings in 
the neighboring wall street area of southern manhattan 
the new york feds contingency system of dieselpowered 
generators had been operating the fedwire since the blackout 
but bakstansky said one of the generators began to falter 
thursday and fed officials decided to take the precautionary step 
of relocating the entire operation to an emergency backup site in 
pearl river ny a northern suburb that caused a slight delay in 
fedwire transactions he said 
it was a matter of reconnecting the banks to a new site he 
said we consulted with banks all through the morning and by 11 
am we were on line with securities transfers by 1115 we were on 
line with funds transfers 
he said if the new york fed hadnt opened the fedwire banks in 
the area couldnt have completed ordinary transfers of money and 
likely would have been forced to severely curtail operations or 
perhaps close for the day 
the pearl river location was an emergency site developed by the 
new york fed in 1987 in case such a power problem arose bakstansky 
said 
it was unclear how soon the operation would be able to return to 
manhattan he said 
</TEXT>
