<TEXT>
the securities and exchange commission filed 
suit wednesday against imprisoned zzzz best owner barry minkow 
claiming he violated securities law in connection with his 
nowdefunct carpetcleaning business 
the federal complaint stemming from allegedly fraudulent 
financial statements filed with the commission in 1986 also names 
13 of minkows associates 
most of them have already agreed to permanent injunctions 
barring them from engaging in violations of the securities laws 
said sec attorney karen matteson 
the complaint alleges that minkow exaggerated the companys 
revenues so he could more easily sell stock in the firm 
the compliant says he attributed nearly half of zzzz bests 5 
million 1986 revenue figure and 86 percent of its 1987 first 
quarter revenue figure of 5 million to nonexistent insurance 
restoration business matteson said 
minkow raised 15 million by selling stock in the company 
matteson said 
the complaint also alleges that minkow lied on statements that 
showed the company had at least 2 million in assets so it could be 
listed by the national association of securities dealers inc 
automated quotation system the stock exchange known as nasdaq 
matteson said 
that listing makes it easier for the public to buy and sell 
your stock matteson said 
the purpose of filing the complaint is so the sec can prosecute 
on contempt charges possibly criminal if the defendants violate 
the injunction matteson said 
minkows attorney david kenner said he was surprised by the 
sec action 
theyre a day late and a dollar short in connection with this 
matter for failure for what they should have done a long time 
ago kenner said 
minkow 24 founded the carpetcleaning company in his parents 
garage when he was 15 years old he ultimately was charged with 57 
counts of securities credit card and mail fraud in connection with 
a scheme to bilk investors and banks of more than 100 million 
minkow was convicted last year and is serving 25year sentence 
at a federal prison in colorado a federal judge also ordered 
minkow to pay 26 million in restitution 
